05051nam a22007575i 9780824861902DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t19981998hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1041989246  a(OCoLC)1046616100  a(OCoLC)1047015234  a(OCoLC)1049632851  a(OCoLC)1054881630  a97808248619027 a10.1515/97808248619022doi  a(DE-B1597)483991  a(OCoLC)1021221037  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBR1307b.M85 1998eb 7aREL0070002bisacsh04a275.22211 aMullins, Mark R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChristianity Made in Japan :bA Study of Indigenous Movements /cMark R. Mullins. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNanzan Library of Asian Religion and Culture ;v2500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Christianity as World Religion and Vernacular Movement -- t2. The Social Sources of Christianity in Japan -- t3. Charisma, Minor Founders, and Indigenous Movements -- t4. The Fountainhead of Japanese Christianity Revisited -- t5. Christianity as a Path of Self-Cultivation -- t6. Japanese Versions of Apostolic Christianity -- t7. Japanese Christians and the World of the Dead -- t8. Comparative Patterns of Growth and Decline -- t9. The Broader Context of Japanese Christianity -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGeneral Bibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor centuries the accommodation between Japan and Christianity has been an uneasy one. Compared with others of its Asian neighbors, the churches in Japan have never counted more than a small minority of believers more or less resigned to patterns of ritual and belief transplanted from the West. But there is another side to the story, one little known and rarely told: the rise of indigenous movements aimed at a Christianity that is at once made in Japan and faithful to the scriptures and apostolic tradition. Christianity Made in Japan draws on extensive field research to give an intriguing and sympathetic look behind the scenes and into the lives of the leaders and followers of several indigenous movements in Japan. Focusing on the "native" response rather than Western missionary efforts and intentions, it presents varieties of new interpretations of the Christian tradition. It gives voice to the unheard perceptions and views of many Japanese Christians, while raising questions vital to the self-understanding of Christianity as a truly "world religion."This ground-breaking study makes a largely unknown religious world accessible to outsiders for the first time. Students and scholars alike will find it a valuable addition to the literature on Japanese religions and society and on the development of Christianity outside the West. By offering an alternative approach to the study and understanding of Christianity as a world religion and the complicated process of cross-cultural diffusion, it represents a landmark that will define future research in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aChristian sectszJapan. 0aChristianity and culturezJapan. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486190240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824861902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824861902.jpg  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pr